                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1627">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.0144/20.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Chargé
                            <persName type="to">O’Shaughnessy</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1501.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-12">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 12, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I enclose herewith a copy of a despatch from the
                    Consul at Nuevo Laredo, in regard to the kidnapping of Samuel Cantu on American
                    territory by Mexican federal officers. You will bring to the attention of the
                    appropriate authorities the abuses committed by the military leaders in Nuevo
                    Laredo and request that immediate action be taken to put a stop thereto.</p>
                <p>You will add that the lawless disposition of the commander at Nuevo Laredo, as
                    shown by his disregard of international rights and obligations, appears to
                    suggest the propriety of his removal from his present position of command
                    adjacent to the borders of the United States, where his acts have already tended
                    to create grave international complications.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>For the Secretary of State: <lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">J. B. Moore</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
